04506nam a22005175i 9780822386261DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223862617 a10.1515/97808223862612doi  a(DE-B1597)553306  a(OCoLC)1226679619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1998.3.C36bS66 2004 7aPER0040102bisacsh04a791.4302/33/0922221 aSmoodin, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRegarding Frank Capra :bAudience, Celebrity, and American Film Studies, 1930–1960 /cEric Smoodin. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (314 p.) :b31 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Audiences, Film Studies, and Frank Capra -- t1 The National and the Local: Ballyhoo and the U.S. Film Audience -- t2 Regulating National Markets: Chinese Censorship and The Bitter Tea of General Yen -- t3 Film Education and Quality Entertainment for Children and Adolescents -- t4 This Business of America: Mr. Smith, John Doe, and the Politicized Viewer -- t5 Coercive Viewings: Soldiers and Prisoners Watch Movies -- t6 Politics and Pedagogy near the End of a Career: From Feature Films to Television Production -- tConclusion: The Contemporary Capra -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this innovative historical examination of the American movie audience, Eric Smoodin focuses on reactions to the films of Frank Capra. Best known for his Hollywood features—including It Happened One Night, It’s a Wonderful Life, and Mr. Smith Goes to Washington—Capra also directed educational films, military films, and documentaries. Based on his analysis of the reception of a broad range of Capra’s films, Smoodin considers the preferences and attitudes toward Hollywood of the people who watched movies during the “Golden Age” of studio production, from 1930 to 1960.Drawing on archival sources including fan letters, exhibitor reports, military and prison records, government and corporate documents, and trade journals, Smoodin explains how the venues where Capra’s films were seen and the strategies used to promote the films affected audience response and how, in turn, audience response shaped film production. He analyzes issues of foreign censorship and government intervention in the making of The Bitter Tea of General Yen; the response of high school students to It Happened One Night; fan engagement with the overtly political discourse of Meet John Doe and Mr. Smith Goes to Washington; San Quentin prisoners’ reaction to a special screening of It’s a Wonderful Life; and at&t’s involvement in Capra’s later documentary work for the Bell Science Series. He also looks at the reception of Capra’s series Why We Fight, used by the American military to train recruits and re-educate German prisoners of war. Illuminating the role of the famous director and his films in American culture, Regarding Frank Capra signals new directions for significant research on film reception and promotion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386261zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386261423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822386261/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles